data.content:
## What breaks

In EF Core 11, the Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. The `EnableSyncOverAsync()` / `AllowSynchronousIO` escape hatch you relied on in .NET 10 no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` against the Cosmos provider will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime.

## The fix

Convert to async all the way through:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Operators → `ToListAsync()`, `FirstAsync()`, `CountAsync()`, `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Callers must `await` — this typically cascades up through controllers/services ("async all the way down")

The Cosmos SDK is inherently async; the old sync path just wrapped `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` internally, risking deadlocks. This removal forces the correct pattern.
